A first virtual operator will win Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't miss it for long.
We have mentioned, on many occasions, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
As a result of the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of less expensive Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czechia remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is far more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (Czech Telecommunications Office (Czech Telecommunications Office), who said several times that there was no longer any room for another operator in Chechnya, is crying with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network does not seem to have much more chance (however, it would now find only difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable decrease in prices, which should subsequently also react to conventional operators.
However, even before the entry of the parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those heard today at our home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We are not obliged to go looking too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they do need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from relatively high construction, operating and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as expensive as its competitors in Britain.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, putting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
\"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator who pleases them and to whom they can trust,\" said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesperson, doubting: \"Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services -
In Czechia, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in Czechia are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area, - said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in Czechia were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not been hiding, for a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations, says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
The future is therefore perhaps promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
\"At the moment, we do not consider that there is a place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific markets.
For the time being, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us, - said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificness of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with the declaration of O2: “We have not registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project for the time being, which could serve as a basis”
And it adds: \"It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement -
Vodafone instead directs his attention to the fulfilment of requests to obtain his own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says in this regard: \"We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
That is what we believe means the most contributions from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet -
The responsible authorities: in progress with the operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have resulted in a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profit.
So what good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators can hear themselves as larons in the fair. The girl accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTU, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This information is accessible to the public from the ČTU web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon stands ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: \"Competition in the mobile market has also recently been enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is evident that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and above all its services, to high requirements -
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disappointing.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTU, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in Chechnya.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts its typical position in the face of this problem.
-The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the time being, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously shown sufficient interest for conventional operators, - it has specified in response to our question Kristián Chalupa from the department of external relations of the ÚOHS.
A statement thus made would not be surprising by the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers, and on the other hand also take care, so that no one takes advantage of their position on the market, such a declaration is more than misleading.
In particular, Kristián Chalupa adds: “Outside, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services”
However, to put pressure on the honest functioning of the market and to lower prices does not appear to be part of the interests of the UOOHS.
What is really shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which derives from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, is naturally posed.
In the same way, a price of essence strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and the hard fight of competition.
The Office did not, in this regard, note any signs of anti-competitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in any way or any other.
None of the operators have a dominant position, and therefore none of them has an increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed for opening up the mobile market to virtual operators are likely to be missing even from the Telecommunications Regulator, as stated in Chaloupa's statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTU that telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different vision of things: in order to create a virtual operator possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how he must play a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators are doing visibly in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested people (including the previously mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Returning responsibility to the ČTU is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes hands of the case.
We have already met with this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to move forward in the development of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an extension of the powers of the ČTU on the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests appear to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
However, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo-operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies publishing their own list of mobile phone services, but the mobile phone services are only public in part.
In most cases, it is a matter of companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally reach only elected members.
The magic tower consists in the fact that the company is in front of the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she obtains special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
\"If what you were talking about happened, it could be a transgression of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could result in a halt of collaboration with the society in question,\" answered our question on this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that such an activity could not be heard even by mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
There is no operator, however, against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, while at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: “The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary mobile operators customers -
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTU.
In addition, there is another question in the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to unveil such an activity, and if it does not wish to be limited to explanations from operators, who claim that they have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has resulted in a significant decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were increasingly striving to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by them were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries were involved, not in the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators deal with this issue in the way a hot potato is disposed of by transmitting it to a close target.
As a result of our experiences, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable to them.
But let's not miss it after the cognac.
If the sliding information says true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market will perhaps return to motion.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS can hardly remain unfavourable in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mŭj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiaáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek sees Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech Public Radio), he chose to interpret the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
\"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have a good dictionary, so that we understand the words, that they sing simultaneously,\" he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov mŭj played for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), Czech original piece of Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the Czech independent Republic.
