Common Transport (MHD) Pragois will introduce, Wednesday, the chip into their ticketing system
On Wednesday, 1 October 2008, it will be recorded in the history of Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Pragoese Transportation Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will be placed in the metro, trams and buses, which, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a coupon 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time record it on their chip card at the information points and Dopravní podnik offices (the Transportation Agency), located at the Muzeum, Mŭstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka Metro stations.
From yesterday, there is also the opportunity to buy coupons online on the Dopravní podnik web pages: www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people took advantage of the service in the morning.
Those who start using the online store can permanently forget the windows at the subway stations, where they had to so far trample impatience in long tails in order to obtain paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupons online and will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
“In these contact points, there is at the disposal of passengers a window with trained staff, who will help those interested with internet purchase and will also record the coupon they bought on their card,” says the spokesman for the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to record the electronic coupons on the Opencard in automatic distributors installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, reminding the machines to compose the tickets and the passengers may have already noticed them at Roztyly Metro stations, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
\"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be ninety,\" Opatrný added.
An automatic will control the coupon instead of the driver
The machines that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
