The Southeast called for a referendum in the USA
The Germans of the Southeast asked in 1945 for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Germans from the South were allegedly addressing the President of the United States with such a desire.
This is due among other things to a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov ask in the letter the American President not to allow only - šumavská župa - (region of forests in the south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
\"We have understood the situation and want to be absolutely sure that the words that the U.S. troops come to the territory of Germany not in oppressors and enemies, but in liberators,\" are written in the letter, signed \"People, to whom the fate of Šumava is at heart.\"
Since the alliance with Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without respect, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
\"We cannot believe that you would give this territory to a foreign State to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of millions of inhabitants,\" is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the \"Czech oppressors\"
If the president of the USA doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or to live under the United States patronity.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Southeast of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least had to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them were given such an opportunity.
Some expected the United States and Britain to obtain for the Southeast a certain type of autonomy.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
\"They thought that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them,\" said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war estimated, according to him, that, following the Beneš decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
