Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach escapes in the face of danger, which means he's also afraid?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of it: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine \"Edge\" contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presented in a series of articles of the answers to the question \"What do you think you are true without being able to prove it?\"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of conscience without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or in general of consciousness, we enter hard-to-practice fields because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he makes death, flees, or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective life.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective life to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the Prefrontal Lateral Cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and management and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and seems to be completely absent from other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our conscience that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, including the awareness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant characteristic could reside in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
