No heels, no outer garments.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, released from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and the stolen glances of artists who do not care to get on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in \"Flamenco - people - the theatricality of a few plays with singers, dancers and guitarists with this least known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco under different angles.
Included in the Flemish Photography Month's programming, the exhibition \"reflects the international importance of flamenco, larger every day\" explains the creator, who clarifies that \"Flamenco - people\" may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed - in the street - are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture personality moments of these artists you don't have to make pictures on stage.
They have a distinct personality and character.
What interested me was creating an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of the flamenco stars' personality.
With the festival-Popular Song of Mines- Bauer started a long trip in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plated camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, commemorate the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of the flamenco according to Bauer: \"A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises each day\"
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captured the audience with his art.
The search for essentials and magic was the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
The flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about sixty-six photographic artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exposed to the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the \"Portraits of old sports\" (SportARTproject).
Although the concepts are different in -Flamenco - people - the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a moment more or less long.
I believe that the portrait in photography is the most difficult kind.
You find yourself in front of people, characters you sometimes don't know, or who just give you a few minutes to get a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.
This collection of portraits of the actual flamenco that is called \"Flamenco - people\" is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at the number 20 of the Rue de la Mata (in parallel with the People's of Hercules) which will be opened until 16 October next.
