Talk when sleeping
Some kids talk during the night.
I do not report to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It's a benign sleep disturbance that's called somnoloquia.
This is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking during the night.
This phenomenon may appear in a very sporadic way (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There are no unique causes that determine its appearance
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (peak to bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very strong fevers, stress or overexcitation situations.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or on the contrary with screams, cries, long speeches ...
In the event that somnoloquia becomes very frequent, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation of this problem.
We said that it is a benign alteration, that is why there is no treatment, except if it is related to another sleep disturbance that can be cured (e.g., if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What we can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, search for quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them relax internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the dreamloquies appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Helpful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'll wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and then rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, he is advised to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because when you sleep, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thinking.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming of, then pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only takes a few minutes.
