Hema-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Dr. Francine Descary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the public's confidence that it had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service have been contaminated by acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the horror of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which sought to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer recur.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, only 38% of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood and working products on the ground over the years that followed, we had renewed public confidence - she said before proudly affirming that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Descary, however, maintains that trust is something extremely fragile.
Upon its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time in Europe, there were many cases of human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which has been strong since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations in the Krever and Gelineau reports was that when one does not know and a serious disease can result from this, then the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are established.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of those who had lived in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that has been applied made sense -
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: Nucleic Acid (TAN) tests that directly detect in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies to the virus, which were based on the tests used so far.
TANs have been able to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowledge and not being able to detect them.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people are at risk of HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I think we can feel comfortable today receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover the health, says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant - continues Dr. Décary before stressing that, in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
The need is increasing because the population is old.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
Every healthy person, 18 years of age and older, may nevertheless give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is prevented, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so frightened, it is rarely time to spend an hour giving his blood - it's sunny Francine Descary.
