Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease in Hungary is mentioned among the first causes of death.
Patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary are estimated to be 100 miles away, but only seven miles follow treatment. This is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowishness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases caused differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are spread primarily in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood viruses and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against A and B viruses is recommended. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year a million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogenic gene snores the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world are counted.
Since the disease can be detected by a laboratory routine examination, it is advisable to consult your treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick of the four corners of the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
