Smart Car Imitating Bordon's Flight
What would be the best way to develop technologies that can avoid an obstacle if it is not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CATEEC, which took place in Japan, the budding bees gave the strategic idea of departure to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how they must design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a self-robotized, bio-inspired, BR23C-type, which he has equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
On flights, each bee is its own, oval-shaped space, which in fact looks very much like our safe protective hull - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the department of research and development and technological public relations of the brand.
The bee face-to-face eye plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face-to-face eye, engineers addressed the idea of laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system at present, this avoidance maneuver is carried out in an instinctive way.
\"If this was not the case, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,\" says Toshiyuki Andoh, the Director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and instantaneously, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the time being the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a glance.
To the opposite of bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations of bees to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotary movement, acceleration and slowing as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot were used.
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is greater, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
Andoh says it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism must only deal with a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
We don't need a memory of giga-bytes, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entry into mass-made cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
