Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - the Central Statistical Office of Hungary reports.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to those of July 2008, while compared to those of a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those in the previous month, and 3.2 per cent compared to those in the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry have suffered only a slight increase of 0.1 percent over July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with firstly the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the product and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
The result was deflation in the oil processing sectors (0.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have recorded an increase of 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the areas of electricity, gas, steam and water supply, which is a major factor in national industrial exploitation, prices have increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a comparison of twelve months, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector have been the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverages and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases have evolved between 0.6 per cent and 9.1 per cent.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 percent during the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7% in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, it was the start-up investment profit sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in energy and material production was observed for subsequent transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was 6.8 per cent, while for profit-initiating sectors, there was a 1.4 per cent decrease.
Export sales prices for the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they suffered a decrease of 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment system weakened by 1.7 percent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 percent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and by 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
