Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market knows no crisis
According to the latest investigation by Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
\"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding the entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high global costs that the families of origin must support,\" explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand on the part of the students has so distorted the market that a process of generalized increase has begun even for the residents.
In most cases, rental offers also include a series of violations: free, unregistered, non-loans, sub-locations.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are needed to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes approximately 450 euros; for a single room, there is a minimum of 650 euros (Black Band), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, an average bed costs 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students focus in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a double bed, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), approximately 600 euros are required for a simple, 450 for a double bed.
Smaller values (550 euro for a simple one) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
It can only be saved if one moves away in the peripheral areas: €300 for a bed, and €450 for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes EUR 300/400, for a simple, we spend EUR 400 to 600, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 euros for a single one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent asked for foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Adieu old cinema Paradiso, the cities elude the historical halls.
The historical cinemas ferment in favor of the Multiplex.
\"A city without cinemas is a blind town, it's like a face without eyes\"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the great Italian urban centres, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of the marginalization of cinemas, with the birth of the great multisalleys, and the death of consumption of monorooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that appears to us to be inescapable and undisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and memory-sufficient, - it is as if one of my friends was disappearing, someone we know, with whom we shared a end of the way and so many emotions - watch the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Jury of Cannes, and who told about the poetry of a province hall, and the nostalgia of a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: over the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that have mainly paid the fees: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is headed with 82 single cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multisale cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
\"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally,\" says Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, \"it is useful to build new structures, but it should also guarantee the survival of those who already exist, because when a firm hall in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit for traders: the state's past debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million a year.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first such in Italy, to defend and promote mono cinemas rooms of historic and peripheral centres.
Among the planned regulations, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the area with limited circulation, and will have special rates for parking and certain parking spaces.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” said Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is clear, however, that, in order to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make - New Paradise cinema - to which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so much shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the dark signs through the dust.
