When the energy comes from waves, the big ones start.
This is an overcrowded deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the big world energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossus like Chevron set eyes, and now they try to put their hands on it.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the oil price dropped, around 1980, the idea of using marine energy was put aside, but now the ecological bodies and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector
London's World Energy Council (WEC) estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity requirement could be covered by sea coal operating systems.
This amount would be twice that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Hang on to the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was the Energys, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, we would have said a true revolutionary step.
At two years of this, more and more candidates from these companies have always dedicated to traditional energy put on marine energy.
\"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,\" said a company's spokesperson associated with the American oil colossus, on the Wall Street Journal economic daily, and evaluates the opportunities to cooperate with us.
The cooperation in question relates to obtaining a permit deliberated by the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to give rise to a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if we consider that right in Alaska, the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for further excavations
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. From New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which go through the path of energy from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
The experts are talking about technology at its beginnings, because marine energy does not dispel the fear of ecological impact.
Currently, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create a major ecosystem problem.
To produce large-scale energy, however, technology must be used with a higher ecological impact.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a mud system connected to each other.
The push of the waves, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Energy is sent to the shore through marine cables.
For the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and a part of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the contrary, already produces energy for a commercial center and a parking using six turbines under New York's East River Marines.
The movement of water during tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that fuels a generator.
Verdant has announced that he has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to push energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for Energy Research, is now worth the potential of tides.
Although this is intermittent, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it's just about the energy of tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, with others, look to the shores, invested $7 million and a half dollars in 2008 and foresees investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
